    <p>Before we move on, check out a similar example <a href="http://codepen.io/amhayslip/pen/PZEYPa">here</a>. How would we get all the rest boxes to line up side-by-side? Give it a try with your parntner before moving on.</p>

    <p>The main reason that all of our boxes are starting on a new line is becuase "divs" are by default displayed as "block" elements, which means they take up the entire row their parent. Okay, then why not just to change their display to inline? Try that now. Add the following CSS to the ".small-box"</p>

    <p>Oh crap. They disappeared. This is becuase our "divs" have no content inside of them and inline elements must always have some kind of contant. Strange, right? Instead, change the display to this:</p>

    <pre style="background:#000;color:#f8f8f8">display: inline-block;</pre>

    <p>Hooray! The display, <strong>inline-block</strong> is the best of both worlds. It behaves as a block level element on the inside, but allows content to flow around it like an inline element.</p>

    <p>Now remove that CSS you just added and instead write:</p>

    <pre style="background:#000;color:#f8f8f8">float: left;</pre>

    <p>Float gave us a similar result, but with some undesired side-effects. Notice that the big blue box is just awkwardly hanging out bebind the red ones. This is because the blue box is now "ignoring" the red ones. This is becuase the float CSS property specifies that an element should be taken from the normal flow and placed along the left or right side of its container (depending), where text and inline elements will wrap around it.‚Äù</p>

    <p>Because of this, it's best to use avoid using float unless your plan is the <strong>float all it's siblings as well</strong>.</p>
